<div class="hero">
  <div class="badge">April 2026 Edition</div>
  <h1>Where <em>Pitch</em> Meets <em>Multiple</em> &amp; Neither Blinks First</h1>
  <p>M&amp;A · Market Intelligence · Historical Perspective · The Edge</p>
</div>

<div class="pb">
  <div class="pbn">1</div>
  <div class="pbt">The Hook, Market Intelligence &amp; Legacy</div>
  <div class="pbs">Riddle · High-Five · History</div>
</div>

<div class="p1-grid">

  <div class="p1-col p1-riddle">
    <div class="slabel">The Top Out</div>
    <h2>The Riddle of the Month</h2>
    <hr style="height:2px;background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--sky),transparent);border:none;margin:8px 0 20px">

    <div style="background:rgba(255,255,255,.06);border-left:4px solid var(--sky);border-radius:4px;padding:20px;margin-bottom:20px">
      <p style="color:#ddd;font-size:14px;line-height:1.7;margin-bottom:0"><strong style="color:var(--light-blue)">I'm feared on job sites when the angle is wrong and welcomed in boardrooms when the number is right. I make a building's water run away and make an investor's IRR sprint toward the light. A flatter version of me makes the shingles weep; a steeper version makes the GP leap.</strong></p>
      <p style="color:var(--sky);font-size:13px;font-style:italic;margin-top:12px;margin-bottom:0">What am I?</p>
    </div>

    <p style="color:var(--fg3);font-size:11.5px;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:0">↓ Answer revealed at the end of this issue.</p>

    <div style="margin-top:32px;border-top:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.1);padding-top:20px">
      <div class="slabel" style="margin-bottom:10px">Why It Matters</div>
      <p style="color:#aac;font-size:12px;line-height:1.6;margin-bottom:0">The best operators in this sector are the ones who have translated field chaos into predictable process. <em style="color:var(--light-blue)">That</em> translation is where enterprise value lives — and where the riddle resolves itself every time.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="p1-col p1-hf">
    <div class="slabel">Section A — Market Intelligence</div>
    <h2>The Monthly High-Five</h2>
    <p class="sub">Five headlines. Zero fluff. The moves that matter this month.</p>

    <div class="hl-item">
      <div class="hl-n">1</div>
      <div>
        <span class="htag tma">M&amp;A</span>
        <div class="hl-h">QXO's $3B War Chest — 7 Targets in Late-Stage Talks</div>
        <div class="hl-a">Post-Beacon, QXO has Apollo-backed capital targeting $1B–$5B revenue operators in the U.S. and Europe. 20 targets evaluated; 7 in deep diligence.</div>
        <div class="hl-sw">⚡ Entry window is explicitly narrowing. Move or get priced out.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hl-item">
      <div class="hl-n">2</div>
      <div>
        <span class="htag tsc">Distribution</span>
        <div class="hl-h">Big 3 Choke Point: Manufacturers Now Have 3 Customers</div>
        <div class="hl-a">QXO/Beacon + Home Depot/SRS/GMS (8,000-truck fleet) + ABC Supply dominate distribution. Independents squeezed; manufacturer leverage at contractor level eroding.</div>
        <div class="hl-sw">⚡ Platform cost-per-square negotiation just got structurally harder.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hl-item">
      <div class="hl-n">3</div>
      <div>
        <span class="htag tsc">Supply Chain</span>
        <div class="hl-h">Steel 50%. Chemical Tariffs 272%. Shingles Up 6–10%.</div>
        <div class="hl-a">Section 232 tariffs doubled mid-2025. MDI/TCPP (adhesives, fire retardants) hit 272%. National avg. re-roof now ~$19,800. Structural repricing, not transitory.</div>
        <div class="hl-sw">⚡ Backlog-heavy operators are absorbing margin compression today.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hl-item">
      <div class="hl-n">4</div>
      <div>
        <span class="htag tpe">PE Activity</span>
        <div class="hl-h">56 Platforms. 134 Deals in 2024. Multiples at 6–9x EBITDA.</div>
        <div class="hl-a">Platform count up 239% since early 2023. Top 3 hold &lt;6% of a $100B market. Multiples normalized from 8–11x peak — textbook roll-up runway intact.</div>
        <div class="hl-sw">⚡ Right entry point. But 56 platforms chasing the same bolt-ons.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hl-item">
      <div class="hl-n">5</div>
      <div>
        <span class="htag treg">Regulatory</span>
        <div class="hl-h">Illinois Drops Licensing. DOL 1099 Rule Still Looming.</div>
        <div class="hl-a">IL roofing license repealed Jan 1, 2026 — lower barriers, more fragmentation. DOL contractor reclassification could reprice labor for subcontractor-heavy platforms.</div>
        <div class="hl-sw">⚡ Model your W-2 exposure now. Sleeper risk of 2026.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="p1-col p1-history">
    <div class="slabel">Section B — Retrospective</div>
    <h2>Lessons from the Ladder</h2>
    <p class="sub">The history this industry either learned from — or repeats.</p>

    <div class="hcard">
      <h4>The First Roll-Up Wave: What They Got Wrong (Late 1990s–Early 2000s)</h4>
      <p>The first institutional wave imposed uniform labor models on hyper-local markets and centralized procurement before the systems existed to manage it. They paid premium multiples for revenue they couldn't retain post-transition.</p>
      <p>Platforms that survived share one trait: they bought the <em>operator</em> as much as the business — retaining founders with real equity and building tech infrastructure before they needed it.</p>
      <div class="pill">🎓 Earnout structures that ignore workforce continuity are the sector's #1 value destroyer.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="hcard" style="border-top-color:var(--sky);margin-top:14px">
      <h4 style="color:var(--mid-blue)">Katrina (2005) &amp; the 2011 Super Outbreak</h4>
      <p><strong>Katrina:</strong> Gulf Coast labor spiked 40–60% in 90 days. Lead times stretched 6+ months. Undercapitalized shops couldn't manage materials, crews, and insurance timelines simultaneously.</p>
      <p><strong>2011:</strong> 358 tornadoes, $11B insured losses. PE investments in AL/TN/MS in 2012–13 were acquired at peak storm-cycle multiples. When demand normalized, the underlying business was smaller than the thesis assumed.</p>
      <div class="pill">🎓 Storm EBITDA ≠ recurring EBITDA. Always normalize the trailing twelve.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

<div class="pb">
  <div class="pbn">2</div>
  <div class="pbt">The Edge</div>
  <div class="pbs">Technology · Key Metric · Bottom Line</div>
</div>
<div class="page">
  <section>
    <div class="slabel">Technology Spotlight</div>
    <h2>The Estimating Stack Is Now a Moat</h2>
    <p style="font-size:13px;color:var(--fg2);margin-bottom:4px">AI and drone adoption have moved from operational upgrade to acquisition differentiator — PE buyers are pricing the gap directly into the multiple.</p>
    <hr class="rule">
    <p>AI use among roofing contractors jumped from 29% in 2024 to 40% in 2025. Among top operators, drone-enabled inspection and AI estimating have become table stakes. Contractors delivering drone-backed proposals within hours of a storm event are structurally closing more business than those with ladders and clipboards.</p>

    <div class="sg">
      <div class="sc">
        <h4>Drone inspection speed</h4>
        <p>Residential inspection in under 30 min vs. several hours manually. AI classifies hail strikes, membrane blistering, and flashing failures automatically — GPS-tagged and insurance-ready. FAA projects 18% annual growth in drone inspection services.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sc">
        <h4>AI estimating (EagleView, Hover, RoofSnap)</h4>
        <p>Satellite + drone imagery generates estimates with live material pricing and local labor rates. 70% faster cycle times. Higher close rates in competitive multi-bid environments — especially critical in the 48-hour post-storm window.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sc">
        <h4>Predictive maintenance → recurring revenue</h4>
        <p>AI platforms trigger proactive outreach before roof failure, converting one-time project revenue into service agreements. Recurring revenue is the single most reliable driver of a premium exit multiple in this sector.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="sc">
        <h4>Insurance automation</h4>
        <p>Drone data piped directly into claim workflows provides GPS-verified, time-stamped documentation that speeds payment cycles and reduces supplement leakage — one of the most persistent margin drains on insurance-heavy books.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="slabel" style="margin-top:36px">Key Metric of the Month</div>
    <h2>Revenue Per Crew Per Day (RPCD)</h2>
    <hr class="rule">

    <div class="metric-hero">
      <div>
        <div class="metric-unit">Target Benchmark</div>
        <div class="metric-num">$8K</div>
        <div style="color:var(--light-blue);font-size:14px;margin-top:4px;font-weight:600">Revenue Per Crew Per Day</div>
        <p style="color:var(--pale-blue);font-size:12px;margin-top:10px;margin-bottom:0;line-height:1.5">The operational heartbeat of a roofing business. If you don't track RPCD, you don't know if you're making money until it's too late.</p>

        <div class="metric-benchmarks" style="margin-top:20px">
          <div style="font-size:10px;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:2px;text-transform:uppercase;color:var(--light-blue);margin-bottom:10px">Industry Benchmarks</div>
          <div class="bench-row">
            <div class="bench-label">Struggling operator</div>
            <div class="bench-bar-bg"><div class="bench-bar-fill" style="width:30%;background:var(--mid-gray)"></div></div>
            <div class="bench-val">&lt;$4K</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bench-row">
            <div class="bench-label">Average operator</div>
            <div class="bench-bar-bg"><div class="bench-bar-fill" style="width:55%;background:var(--light-blue)"></div></div>
            <div class="bench-val">~$6K</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bench-row">
            <div class="bench-label">PE-ready operator</div>
            <div class="bench-bar-bg"><div class="bench-bar-fill" style="width:75%;background:var(--sky)"></div></div>
            <div class="bench-val">$8K+</div>
          </div>
          <div class="bench-row">
            <div class="bench-label">Top-quartile platform</div>
            <div class="bench-bar-bg"><div class="bench-bar-fill" style="width:100%;background:#fff"></div></div>
            <div class="bench-val">$12K+</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="metric-right">
        <p><strong>What it measures:</strong> Total daily revenue divided by the number of active crews on the job that day. A crew is typically 3–5 workers plus a lead. This single number tells you whether your crews are sized right, your jobs are sequenced efficiently, and your materials are arriving on time.</p>
        <p><strong>Why PE buyers care:</strong> RPCD is a pre-diligence filter. An operator running $8K+ RPCD across 5+ crews has solved three hard problems simultaneously: labor productivity, job scheduling, and material logistics. Operators below $5K consistently reveal hidden dysfunction in the diligence process — scope creep, rework, and crew downtime that doesn't show up in the P&amp;L until after close.</p>
        <p><strong>How to improve it:</strong> AI estimating reduces scope error; drone inspections cut pre-job rework; CRM pipeline tools prevent crew idle days. The technology stack on page 1 of this section directly feeds this number — which is why tech-enabled operators command the premium multiples they do.</p>
        <p style="margin-bottom:0"><strong>Watch-out:</strong> A high RPCD on residential combined with low commercial exposure can be misleading — residential crews run faster but are more storm-dependent. Normalize for mix before comparing across markets.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <h3>The Ridge Report Bottom Line</h3>
      <p>The roofing industry in April 2026 is a $100B market still waiting to be consolidated — but the math is getting harder. With 56 PE platforms competing for the same fragmented operators, and QXO alone holding $3B in dry powder and seven deals in late diligence, the era of easy entry pricing is closing. <strong>The multiple you earn at exit will be determined by decisions made right now:</strong> the tech stack you build, the recurring revenue you sign, and the operational systems you put in place before a buyer's diligence team arrives.</p>
      <p>Operators who track RPCD, run drone-enabled estimating, and maintain CRM-visible pipelines are not just better businesses — they are <strong>de-risked businesses</strong>, and in a market where 56 buyers are hunting the same targets, de-risked businesses get the premium bid. The ones still running on spreadsheets and institutional memory are not just leaving multiple points on the table. They're handing them to the competitor two counties over who already scheduled their drone flight.</p>
      <p style="color:var(--light-blue);font-style:italic">The pitch is steep. The multiples are real. Know your RPCD before someone else tells you what it is.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="answer-box">
      <div class="alabel">Riddle Answer — Page 1</div>
      <p><strong>Answer: Pitch.</strong> In roofing, pitch (slope) determines drainage and structural integrity — too flat and you get ponding water; steep is better. In private equity, a "pitch" is the investor presentation, and a steeper growth story signals a more compelling multiple. Same word. Entirely different anxieties — and somehow, the same consequences when you get it wrong.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
